# t/research/reply-restart-safety.test — the REPLY harvest is crash-safe
# (decision-013), the reply sibling of the memory harvest's crash safety. A
# finished run's email reply is recovered even when assemble-reply never completes
# inline — and it is delivered EXACTLY once, never twice.
#
# agent-run-finished no longer emits assemble-reply as a Cmd — a crash between
# logging that message and the effect finishing would lose the reply (replay
# re-derives the Cmd but SUPPRESSES effects, and mark-reply-queued was never
# logged). Instead it records the run as a PENDING reply job on the tasks model.
# The harvest-reconcile subscription reconstructs the AssembleReplyPayload from the
# logged Task and drives assemble-reply; the effect ends by emitting
# mark-harvested{reply} (cross-module, from email back to tasks), which clears the
# job. A crash before that leaves the job pending, and restart's replay rebuilds it
# so the source fires again.
#
# Exactly-once is what makes re-driving safe: the reply's Message-ID is
# deterministic (per task+run+domain), and AddOutbox is now idempotent on it, so a
# re-driven assemble-reply queues the SAME outbox row — never a second send. This
# proves the FULL crash window: assemble-reply's out/ Harvest read is faulted so the
# effect errors before queuing anything, the process crashes with the job owed, and
# the restart recovers it into ONE outbound. `fail work reply` targets the Harvest
# read, which only assemble-reply calls, so the memory and skill harvests are
# undisturbed.

send allow-sender { address kasi@decode.ee }

# --- Faulted run: assemble-reply's Harvest fails before it queues the reply. ---
fail work reply

deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "banking"
    body    "how should I pay this invoice?"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-agent

agent {
    out reply.txt "Pay it through the approved channel."
}
task 1 status is awaiting-user

# NOTHING went out — the reply harvest errored before AddOutbox, so no outbox row,
# no send.
outbound count is 0
# ...and the run sits with a pending REPLY job, still owed its reply. This is the
# crash window: the reply would be lost forever if HarvestPending were not logged.
model tasks harvest_pending matches "*reply*"

# The process dies and comes back: full-log replay rebuilds the pending reply job
# (the run's References already carry the deterministic reply Message-ID, logged by
# agent-run-finished), then the harvest-reconcile source re-fires — this time
# Harvest succeeds, and the run-harvest handler reconstructs the same reply payload
# from the Task model.
crash
restart

task 1 status is awaiting-user                     # replay rebuilt the model
outbound count is 1                                 # recovered — and EXACTLY one
outbound last body matches "*approved channel*"     # it is the run's reply.txt
model tasks harvest_pending is ""                   # mark-harvested{reply} cleared it — exactly once

# --- Negative control: no fault → the reply lands inline, sent at once. ---
deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "timezone"
    body    "what timezone am I in?"
}
task 2 status is awaiting-agent

agent {
    out reply.txt "You are in Europe/Stockholm."
}
task 2 status is awaiting-user

# The second reply went straight out — total two, each run's reply exactly once.
outbound count is 2
outbound last body matches "*Stockholm*"
model tasks harvest_pending is ""
